Hi,

Michael Baranov wrote:
> Roberto,
> 
> Thanks for your prompt reply.
> Not sure, this is what I came across: 
> http://www.nvnews.net/vbulletin/showthread.php?t=104937

You may try to follow what's in there.

> I'm not sure how the ddc/ci protocol works and what's the  role of video 
> drivers in the chain, but it seem there is no vesa ddc/ci documentation 
> available for any FOSS community. I think it costs around 400USD... if 
> we really need that we could easily raise the money inside the linux 
> community to buy it.

We do not need these specs, Oleg and I (i.e. the original authors)
reversed-engineered the protocol and know quite well how it works.

The problem is often to access the I2C bus on the video card, which is
vendor-specific. For some reasons the manufacturer usually don't provide
the specs to the open-source world.

> Can you recommend anything for me to play with? Like try different 
> drivers (vesa, nv) and/or kernel modules? I'm sure the hardware is OK, 
> because nvidia-settings is able to talk to my monitor and obtain EDID 
> and other info.

Try first with debugging informations: sudo ddccontrol -p -v -v. I don't
expect anything indicating where exactly is the problem, but you could
try and send back the results.

You could try removing all proprietary modules in console mode, load
"nvidiafb" module (compile it if necessary), and see if anything better
happens, in this case a solution might be easy.

Best regards,

Nicolas

